and draws a road map of the obstacles that need to be removed before the challenge of reconciliation can be met. This insightful volume is organized in three parts. The opening chapters examine colonial promises and practices, including the treaty right to education and the establishment of day, residential, and industrial schools. The second part focuses on the legacy of racism, trauma, and dislocation, and the third part explores contemporary issues in curriculum development, assessment, leadership, and governance. This diverse collection reveals the possibilities and problems associated with incorporating Traditional Knowledge and Indigenous teaching and healing practices into school courses and programs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducation and statezCanadaxHistory. 0aEducation and statezCanada. 0aEducation and state. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzCanadaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxResidential schoolsxHistory. 0aOff-reservation boarding schoolszCanadaxHistory. 0aOff-reservation boarding schoolszCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh1 aAnuik, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr-Stewart, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr-Stewart, Sheila, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCottrell, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFellner, Karlee D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardie, Rosalind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Darryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLafond, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLalond